VL  - 48
IS  - 3
SP  - 287
EP  - 312
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/06/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(91)90065-L
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769190065L
AB  - Multi-factor productivity measurement requires information on returns to scale and internal valuations of such quasi-fixed factors as resource inputs. We estimate a translog cost function for the asbestos industry in Canada, and find significant induced technological change and returns to scale. The shadow rental price of reserves is significant and drops sharply after 1975. The productivity index based on the estimated model sharply differs from the Divisia index, as computed from direct measurements under the assumption of constant returns to scale and ignoring the role of the resource as an input.
